        title: 'Social Contract Theory and Political Legitimacy',
        passage: `Social contract theory, developed by philosophers including Hobbes, Locke, and Rousseau, attempts to explain the legitimacy of political authority. According to this tradition, governments derive their authority from an implicit agreement among citizens to surrender certain freedoms in exchange for social order and protection of remaining rights.

Thomas Hobbes, writing during the English Civil War, presented the most pessimistic version. Without government, he argued, life would be "solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short"—a war of all against all. Rational individuals would therefore accept almost any government, even an absolute sovereign, to escape this natural condition.

John Locke offered a more optimistic account. Humans in the state of nature possess natural rights to life, liberty, and property. Government's purpose is to protect these pre-existing rights, not merely to prevent chaos. Crucially, Locke argued that citizens retain the right to revolt against governments that violate their rights—a doctrine that influenced the American Revolution.

Jean-Jacques Rousseau introduced the concept of the "general will." He distinguished between the will of all (mere aggregation of individual preferences) and the general will (what is truly best for the community as a whole). Legitimate government, for Rousseau, expresses the general will, transforming natural freedom into civil freedom. Critics have noted that this concept can justify authoritarianism if leaders claim to know the general will better than citizens themselves.`,
