        title: 'Deep Ocean Ecosystems',
        passage: `The deep ocean, below 200 meters where sunlight cannot penetrate, was long thought to be a biological desert. Scientists assumed that without photosynthesis, little life could exist. The discovery of thriving communities around hydrothermal vents in 1977 revolutionized our understanding of where and how life can flourish.

Hydrothermal vents form where tectonic plates spread apart, allowing seawater to percolate into the crust, become superheated, and return laden with dissolved minerals. The scalding water, reaching temperatures up to 400°C, would kill most organisms. Yet specialized bacteria thrive by chemosynthesis—using chemical energy from hydrogen sulfide rather than sunlight to produce organic matter.

These chemosynthetic bacteria form the base of a unique food web. Giant tube worms, some growing over two meters long, lack digestive systems entirely, instead hosting symbiotic bacteria in their tissues. Ghostly white crabs, shrimp, and fish populate the vents, along with species found nowhere else on Earth. Entire ecosystems exist independent of solar energy.

The discovery raised profound questions about the origins and limits of life. Some scientists hypothesize that life itself may have begun at such vents, where chemical energy and mineral-rich environments provided ideal conditions. The existence of chemosynthetic ecosystems also fuels speculation about life on other worlds—perhaps in the subsurface oceans of Jupiter's moon Europa or Saturn's moon Enceladus.`,
