        id: 'gre_27', category: 'GRE', topic: '科学史', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Thomas Kuhn and Scientific Revolutions',
        passage: `Thomas Kuhn's 1962 book "The Structure of Scientific Revolutions" fundamentally changed how we understand scientific progress. Before Kuhn, science was typically viewed as a cumulative enterprise, with knowledge steadily accumulating as scientists made discoveries and corrected errors. Kuhn proposed a radically different picture.

Central to Kuhn's framework is the concept of paradigm—a constellation of beliefs, values, and techniques shared by a scientific community. During periods of "normal science," researchers work within an accepted paradigm, solving puzzles while taking fundamental assumptions for granted. Anomalies—observations that don't fit the paradigm—are typically set aside or explained away.

When anomalies accumulate and resist resolution, a crisis develops. Scientists may begin questioning basic assumptions and exploring alternative frameworks. Eventually, a new paradigm may emerge that better accounts for problematic observations. This shift constitutes a "scientific revolution"—as when Copernican astronomy replaced Ptolemaic, or Einstein's relativity superseded Newtonian mechanics.

Kuhn controversially argued that paradigm shifts are not purely rational processes. Competing paradigms are "incommensurable"—they differ so fundamentally that direct comparison is difficult. Scientists who adopt new paradigms undergo something like a religious conversion rather than simply weighing evidence. This claim troubled philosophers who viewed science as the epitome of rational inquiry, sparking decades of debate about scientific objectivity.`,
