        title: 'Migration: Nature\'s Great Journeys',
        passage: `Animal migration ranks among the most remarkable phenomena in the natural world. Each year, billions of animals—birds, butterflies, whales, and wildebeest—undertake long journeys between seasonal habitats. These movements, driven by the need for food, favorable climate, or breeding grounds, have fascinated scientists for centuries.

Arctic terns hold the record for the longest migration, traveling from Arctic to Antarctic and back each year—a round trip of roughly 70,000 kilometers. Monarch butterflies migrate up to 4,800 kilometers from Canada to Mexico, remarkable given their tiny size and the fact that no individual butterfly completes the entire round trip; it takes multiple generations.

How animals navigate these vast distances remains partially mysterious. Birds use multiple cues: the sun's position, star patterns, Earth's magnetic field, and even smell. Some species appear to have an inherited "map" that guides first-time migrants to destinations they have never visited. Young birds sometimes learn routes by following experienced adults.

Migration faces increasing threats from human activities. Habitat destruction eliminates critical stopover sites where migrants rest and refuel. Climate change disrupts timing, causing mismatches between animal arrivals and food availability. Light pollution confuses nocturnal migrants, while collisions with buildings and wind turbines kill millions of birds annually.`,
