        title: 'The Great Depression: Causes and Consequences',
        passage: `The Great Depression of the 1930s remains the most severe economic downturn in modern history. Beginning with the American stock market crash of October 1929, it spread worldwide, causing unemployment rates above 25% in many countries and lasting until the outbreak of World War II. Understanding its causes continues to inform economic policy today.

Multiple factors contributed to the catastrophe. The speculative bubble in stock prices was fueled by easy credit and margin buying, allowing investors to purchase stocks with borrowed money. When confidence wavered, panic selling crashed prices, destroying wealth and undermining consumer spending. Banks that had invested in stocks or made risky loans began failing.

The Federal Reserve's response is now widely criticized. Rather than expanding the money supply to support struggling banks and stimulate the economy, the Fed contracted credit, worsening the deflationary spiral. The gold standard prevented international monetary coordination, as countries defended their gold reserves rather than stimulating their economies.

The Depression transformed economic thinking and government's role. John Maynard Keynes argued that insufficient aggregate demand caused prolonged downturns, and that government spending could compensate when private investment collapsed. This Keynesian revolution legitimized active fiscal policy and established the modern welfare state. Central banks now aggressively intervene during crises, determined to avoid the mistakes that deepened the Depression.`,
