        title: 'Graphene: The Wonder Material',
        passage: `Graphene, a single layer of carbon atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice, has been called a "wonder material" for its extraordinary properties. First isolated in 2004 by Andre Geim and Konstantin Novoselov, who won the Nobel Prize for their work, graphene has sparked enormous scientific and commercial interest.

Graphene is the strongest material ever measured—about 200 times stronger than steel by weight—yet incredibly thin and flexible. A one-square-meter sheet would weigh just 0.77 milligrams. It conducts electricity better than copper and heat better than any known material. It is nearly transparent, absorbing only 2.3% of visible light.

These properties suggest numerous applications. In electronics, graphene could enable faster, more efficient transistors and flexible displays. For energy, graphene-enhanced batteries could charge faster and store more energy. Water filtration membranes using graphene could desalinate seawater more efficiently than current methods. Composite materials incorporating graphene could create lighter, stronger structures for aerospace and automotive industries.

Despite two decades of research, commercial applications remain limited. Manufacturing high-quality graphene at scale has proven difficult and expensive. Most current methods produce graphene with defects that compromise its remarkable properties. Researchers continue working on production techniques, and many believe graphene will eventually fulfill its promise, though the timeline remains uncertain.`,
