        title: 'The Origins of Human Cooperation',
        passage: `Human beings cooperate on a scale unmatched by any other species. We build cities, wage wars, create complex economies, and establish institutions—all requiring coordination among thousands or millions of individuals who will never meet. This remarkable capacity for large-scale cooperation has puzzled evolutionary theorists, since natural selection typically favors self-interest.

The puzzle deepens when we observe that humans cooperate even with strangers they will never encounter again, in situations where defection would go unpunished. Classical theories of cooperation, based on kinship or reciprocity, struggle to explain such behavior. Your genes don't benefit when you help an anonymous stranger, and you'll never see them again to collect a return favor.

Some researchers propose that cultural group selection may explain human ultrasociality. Groups with cooperative norms and institutions outcompete less cooperative groups, even if cooperation is costly to individuals within the group. Over time, this process favors psychological tendencies that support cooperation—including capacities for guilt, shame, and concern for reputation.

Others emphasize the role of punishment in sustaining cooperation. Humans not only cooperate but also punish non-cooperators, even at personal cost. This "altruistic punishment" can stabilize cooperation by making defection costly. Cross-cultural experiments confirm that punishment sustains cooperation, though its forms vary across societies.`,
