        title: 'Photosynthesis: Capturing Solar Energy',
        passage: `Photosynthesis is the process by which plants, algae, and some bacteria convert light energy into chemical energy stored in glucose. This fundamental biological process not only sustains virtually all life on Earth but also produced the oxygen that makes our atmosphere breathable.

The process occurs primarily in chloroplasts, organelles containing the green pigment chlorophyll. In the light-dependent reactions, chlorophyll absorbs sunlight, using this energy to split water molecules into hydrogen and oxygen. The oxygen is released as a byproduct—the source of nearly all atmospheric oxygen. The hydrogen is used to produce energy-carrying molecules ATP and NADPH.

In the light-independent reactions, commonly called the Calvin cycle, the plant uses ATP and NADPH to convert carbon dioxide from the air into glucose. This process, called carbon fixation, removes CO2 from the atmosphere and incorporates it into organic molecules. Plants then use glucose as fuel for cellular processes or convert it into structural materials like cellulose.

Photosynthesis has profound global implications. Plants remove approximately 120 billion tons of carbon from the atmosphere annually. Deforestation and land-use changes reduce this carbon sink, contributing to climate change. Understanding photosynthesis may also lead to artificial systems that produce fuels or remove carbon dioxide from the atmosphere.`,
