        id: 'gre_34', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '气象学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'El Niño and Global Weather Patterns',
        passage: `El Niño is a climate pattern that occurs when surface waters in the central and eastern Pacific Ocean become unusually warm. This warming disrupts normal atmospheric circulation, affecting weather patterns around the world. El Niño events typically occur every two to seven years and can last from nine months to two years.

Under normal conditions, trade winds blow from east to west across the Pacific, pushing warm surface water toward Asia. This allows cold, nutrient-rich water to rise along South America's coast—a process called upwelling that supports productive fisheries. During El Niño, trade winds weaken or reverse, allowing warm water to spread eastward and suppressing upwelling.

The effects extend far beyond the Pacific. El Niño typically brings increased rainfall to Peru and Ecuador, often causing floods, while drought afflicts Australia, Indonesia, and parts of Africa. North America experiences milder winters in the north and wetter conditions in the south. These teleconnections—remote effects linked through atmospheric circulation—demonstrate the interconnected nature of Earth's climate system.

La Niña represents the opposite phase, with cooler-than-normal Pacific waters intensifying normal patterns. Scientists monitor Pacific temperatures and winds to predict these events, though forecasting remains imperfect. Understanding El Niño and La Niña has become more urgent as climate change may alter their frequency or intensity.`,
