        id: 'gre_35', category: 'GRE', topic: '美学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'The Philosophy of Art: What Makes Something Art?',
        passage: `Defining art has proven surprisingly difficult. Traditional definitions based on beauty or skill founder on the diversity of modern and contemporary art, much of which deliberately rejects conventional aesthetics. Marcel Duchamp's "Fountain" (1917)—a mass-produced urinal signed with a pseudonym—challenged every assumption about what art could be.

Institutional theories propose that art is whatever the art world—museums, galleries, critics, and artists—accepts as art. This approach explains how readymades and conceptual works qualify as art, but seems circular: the art world recognizes art, but what makes them authoritative? It also struggles with outsider art and works created before art institutions existed.

Functionalist definitions focus on what art does rather than what it is. Art, on this view, provides aesthetic experience, expresses emotion, communicates ideas, or promotes social change. Different works may serve different functions, explaining art's diversity. However, many things provide aesthetic experience or express emotion without being art—a sunset, a heartfelt letter.

Historical definitions argue that something is art if it stands in the right relationship to previous art—extending, responding to, or breaking from artistic traditions. This explains how avant-garde works that reject past conventions can still be art; they are defined by their relationship to what they reject. Yet this seems to exclude the first art ever made and cultures without Western art history.`,
