        id: 'gre_36', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '营养学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'The Science of Nutrition and Health',
        passage: `Nutrition science studies how food affects health, but translating research findings into dietary advice has proven challenging. Studies often contradict each other, and yesterday's health food may become today's dietary villain. Understanding why nutrition research is so difficult helps explain these apparent reversals.

Unlike drug trials, nutrition studies cannot easily use placebo controls. Researchers cannot give one group food and another group nothing. Observational studies, which track what people eat and correlate it with health outcomes, are confounded by countless variables. People who eat more vegetables may also exercise more, smoke less, and have higher incomes—any of which might explain better health.

Randomized controlled trials face practical limitations. Asking people to follow specific diets for years is difficult and expensive. Most dietary effects are modest and accumulate over decades, requiring large samples and long follow-up periods. Short-term studies measuring biological markers may not predict actual disease outcomes.

Despite these challenges, certain nutritional principles enjoy strong support. Eating more vegetables and whole grains while limiting processed foods, added sugars, and excessive saturated fat promotes health. Mediterranean and similar traditional diets consistently show benefits in multiple studies. Beyond these basics, the evidence for specific foods or nutrients is often weaker than media coverage suggests.`,
