        title: 'The Formation of Mountains',
        passage: `Mountains, among Earth's most dramatic landforms, form through various geological processes operating over millions of years. Understanding mountain building, or orogeny, reveals the dynamic forces shaping our planet's surface.

Fold mountains, the most common type, form when tectonic plates collide. The immense pressure crumples and folds rock layers, pushing them upward. The Himalayas formed this way when the Indian subcontinent collided with Asia about 50 million years ago—a collision still continuing today, making the Himalayas the youngest and tallest mountain range on Earth.

Volcanic mountains form differently, built by the accumulation of lava and ash from repeated eruptions. Mount Fuji in Japan and Mount Rainier in Washington exemplify this type. Some volcanic mountains rise from hotspots—plumes of magma rising from deep within the Earth. The Hawaiian Islands are volcanic mountains whose bases sit on the ocean floor.

Fault-block mountains form when enormous blocks of rock are uplifted along faults—fractures in Earth's crust where movement occurs. The Sierra Nevada in California rose when a massive block tilted, creating steep eastern faces and gentler western slopes. The Tetons in Wyoming showcase classic fault-block topography with dramatic, jagged peaks.`,
