        id: 'gre_39', category: 'GRE', topic: '社会心理学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Conformity and Social Influence',
        passage: `Social psychology has documented numerous ways that group pressure influences individual behavior. Solomon Asch's conformity experiments in the 1950s demonstrated this powerfully: participants frequently gave obviously wrong answers to simple questions when confederates unanimously gave those wrong answers first.

Asch found that about 75% of participants conformed at least once over multiple trials, even though the correct answer was clear. When interviewed afterward, some participants reported actually seeing the lines differently; others knew the group was wrong but conformed to avoid standing out. The distinction between private acceptance and public compliance remains important in understanding conformity.

Several factors increase conformity. Unanimity is crucial; even one dissenter dramatically reduces conformity rates. Group size matters up to a point—conformity increases with group size but plateaus around four or five members. Higher task difficulty, cultural values emphasizing harmony, and the presence of authority figures all increase conformity.

The implications extend beyond laboratory settings. Conformity can spread misinformation, perpetuate harmful norms, and silence dissent in organizations. Yet conformity also enables social coordination, cultural transmission, and appropriate deference to expertise. The challenge is distinguishing beneficial conformity from harmful groupthink—a task requiring awareness of how powerfully social situations shape our judgments.`,
