        title: 'The Chemistry of Water',
        passage: `Water, the most abundant compound on Earth's surface, possesses remarkable properties that make it essential for life. These properties arise from water's molecular structure: two hydrogen atoms bonded to one oxygen atom at an angle, creating a polar molecule with uneven charge distribution.

Water's polarity allows hydrogen bonding—weak attractions between the slightly positive hydrogen of one molecule and the slightly negative oxygen of another. These bonds give water unusually high surface tension, allowing insects to walk on water and enabling capillary action that draws water up through plant stems.

Hydrogen bonding also explains water's high specific heat capacity—the amount of energy required to raise its temperature. Water absorbs and releases large amounts of heat with relatively small temperature changes. This property moderates coastal climates, allows organisms to maintain stable body temperatures, and makes water excellent for cooling systems.

Unlike most substances, water expands when it freezes. Ice is less dense than liquid water, which is why ice floats. This seemingly simple fact has profound consequences: frozen surfaces insulate liquid water below, allowing aquatic life to survive winter. If ice sank, lakes and oceans would freeze solid from the bottom up, making complex aquatic life impossible.`,
