        id: 'gre_42', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '建筑学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Sustainable Architecture and Green Building',
        passage: `Sustainable architecture aims to minimize the environmental impact of buildings throughout their lifecycle—from construction through operation to eventual demolition. Given that buildings account for approximately 40% of global energy consumption and a similar share of carbon emissions, green building practices have become increasingly important in addressing climate change.

Passive design strategies reduce energy needs without mechanical systems. Building orientation can maximize winter sunlight while minimizing summer heat gain. Proper insulation, thermal mass, and natural ventilation reduce heating and cooling demands. Traditional architecture in many cultures developed sophisticated passive strategies suited to local climates, knowledge that modern sustainable design often rediscovers.

Active systems complement passive strategies. Solar panels generate electricity; solar thermal systems heat water. Green roofs provide insulation, absorb rainwater, and reduce urban heat islands. Rainwater harvesting and greywater recycling reduce water consumption. Smart building management systems optimize energy use based on occupancy and conditions.

Certification systems like LEED (Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design) provide standards and verification for green buildings. These programs evaluate energy efficiency, water use, materials selection, indoor air quality, and site sustainability. While certification adds costs, studies show green buildings often have lower operating expenses and higher property values, providing economic as well as environmental benefits.`,
