        id: 'gre_44', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '免疫学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'The Immune System: Defense Against Disease',
        passage: `The human immune system provides remarkable protection against pathogens—bacteria, viruses, fungi, and parasites that cause disease. This complex network of cells, tissues, and organs has evolved multiple layers of defense, from physical barriers to sophisticated cellular responses that can recognize and remember specific threats.

The innate immune system provides immediate, non-specific defense. Skin and mucous membranes form physical barriers. If pathogens breach these barriers, phagocytes like macrophages and neutrophils engulf and destroy invaders. Inflammation, though uncomfortable, helps contain infections by increasing blood flow and recruiting immune cells to affected areas.

The adaptive immune system provides targeted responses to specific pathogens. B cells produce antibodies—proteins that bind to particular antigens and mark pathogens for destruction. T cells directly attack infected cells or coordinate immune responses. Crucially, the adaptive system has memory: after encountering a pathogen, it can respond faster and more effectively to subsequent infections. This memory underlies vaccination.

When the immune system malfunctions, serious problems result. Autoimmune diseases occur when the system attacks the body's own tissues—as in rheumatoid arthritis, type 1 diabetes, and multiple sclerosis. Allergies represent overreaction to harmless substances. Immunodeficiency, whether inherited or acquired (as in AIDS), leaves individuals vulnerable to infections that healthy immune systems easily defeat.`,
