        id: 'gre_49', category: 'GRE', topic: '科学哲学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'The Problem of Induction',
        passage: `The problem of induction, famously articulated by David Hume in the 18th century, challenges the rational foundation of scientific reasoning. Scientists routinely infer general laws from particular observations—observing that the sun has risen every day, we conclude it will rise tomorrow. But what justifies this inference from observed cases to unobserved ones?

Hume argued that inductive reasoning cannot be justified by logic or experience. Logically, the conclusion of an inductive argument is never guaranteed by its premises; no matter how many white swans we observe, the next could be black. We cannot justify induction by appeal to its past success without circular reasoning—that argument itself relies on induction (past success predicts future success).

Some philosophers embrace this skeptical conclusion, arguing that scientific knowledge lacks the certainty often attributed to it. Others seek to solve or dissolve the problem. Karl Popper proposed that science advances through falsification rather than induction—scientists propose bold conjectures and then attempt to refute them. Theories that survive rigorous testing are "corroborated" but never proven true.

Bayesian approaches offer another response, treating induction as rational belief updating rather than logical proof. On this view, observations don't prove hypotheses but shift probabilities. After observing many white swans, we rationally increase our confidence that all swans are white, even without certainty. The problem of induction reminds us that scientific knowledge, however reliable, remains provisional and fallible.`,
