        title: 'The Psychology of Music',
        passage: `Music is a human universal—every known culture has some form of music, suggesting deep evolutionary roots. Yet music poses an evolutionary puzzle: unlike language, which clearly aids communication and survival, music's adaptive function is less obvious. Why do humans devote so much time and energy to producing and enjoying organized sound?

Several theories attempt to explain music's origins. Darwin suggested sexual selection: musical ability might signal fitness to potential mates, like a peacock's tail. Others propose music strengthened social bonds, facilitating group cohesion and cooperation through shared rhythm and synchronized movement. Music may also have developed from mother-infant communication, where melodic vocalizations soothe infants and strengthen attachment.

Regardless of its origins, music profoundly affects brain and body. Listening to pleasurable music activates reward circuits, releasing dopamine—the same neurotransmitter involved in food and sex. Music can reduce stress hormones, lower blood pressure, and alleviate pain. These effects have led to growing interest in music therapy for conditions from depression to Parkinson's disease.

Music also shapes memory and emotion in powerful ways. Songs can trigger vivid autobiographical memories, a phenomenon exploited in treating dementia patients. The emotional impact of music in films and advertising demonstrates its power to influence mood and behavior. Understanding how music affects the brain may reveal fundamental principles of human cognition and emotion.`,
