        title: 'Dark Matter and the Structure of the Universe',
        passage: `One of the greatest mysteries in modern physics is that the visible matter we can observe—stars, planets, galaxies—accounts for only about 5% of the universe's total mass-energy content. Approximately 27% consists of dark matter, a substance that neither emits nor absorbs light but exerts gravitational influence on visible matter.

The evidence for dark matter comes from multiple sources. In the 1930s, astronomer Fritz Zwicky observed that galaxies in clusters moved faster than expected based on visible mass alone. Later, Vera Rubin found that stars at the edges of spiral galaxies orbit at unexpectedly high speeds—they should fly off unless held by additional invisible mass. Gravitational lensing, where massive objects bend light from distant sources, also reveals more mass than we can see.

Scientists have proposed various candidates for dark matter particles. WIMPs (Weakly Interacting Massive Particles) remain popular hypotheses, though decades of increasingly sensitive experiments have failed to detect them directly. Alternative candidates include axions, sterile neutrinos, and primordial black holes. Some physicists have proposed modifying gravity laws instead, though these theories struggle to match all observations.

The remaining 68% of the universe consists of dark energy, an even more mysterious force driving accelerating cosmic expansion. Together, dark matter and dark energy suggest that our understanding of the universe remains profoundly incomplete. The search to understand these phenomena drives some of the most ambitious experiments in physics today.`,
