        title: 'Epistemology: The Nature of Knowledge',
        passage: `Epistemology, the philosophical study of knowledge, addresses fundamental questions: What is knowledge? How is it acquired? What distinguishes knowledge from mere belief? These questions have occupied philosophers since antiquity and remain surprisingly difficult to answer definitively.

The traditional definition, dating to Plato, holds that knowledge is justified true belief. To know something, you must believe it, it must be true, and you must have good reasons for believing it. This tripartite analysis seemed adequate for millennia until Edmund Gettier's 1963 paper presented counterexamples where all three conditions are met yet we intuitively deny knowledge is present.

Gettier cases involve beliefs that are true and justified but only accidentally so. Suppose you see what appears to be a sheep in a field and form the belief "there is a sheep in the field." Unknown to you, you're looking at a dog disguised as a sheep—but behind a hill, there happens to be a real sheep. Your belief is true, and your evidence (seeing what looks like a sheep) provides justification. Yet something seems wrong with calling this knowledge.

Responses to the Gettier problem have generated extensive literature. Some propose adding a fourth condition—perhaps that the justification must connect appropriately to the truth. Others argue that knowledge cannot be analyzed into necessary and sufficient conditions. Reliabilism suggests that knowledge requires beliefs produced by reliable cognitive processes, regardless of whether the believer can articulate justification. The debate illuminates how even our most basic concepts resist precise definition.`,
