        id: 'gre_54', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '生理学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Sleep: A Biological Necessity',
        passage: `Sleep is essential for survival, yet its precise biological functions remained mysterious for much of scientific history. We now know that sleep serves multiple critical functions, from memory consolidation to physical restoration to immune system maintenance. Understanding sleep has become increasingly important as modern lifestyles disrupt natural sleep patterns.

Sleep architecture consists of cycles lasting roughly 90 minutes, alternating between non-REM and REM (rapid eye movement) stages. Non-REM sleep progresses from light stages to deep slow-wave sleep, during which the brain shows synchronized neural activity and growth hormone is released. REM sleep features vivid dreams, muscle paralysis, and brain activity resembling wakefulness.

Memory consolidation is a crucial sleep function. During sleep, the brain replays experiences from the day, strengthening neural connections for important memories while pruning unnecessary ones. Studies show that people who sleep after learning perform better on memory tests than those who remain awake. Different types of memories may be consolidated during different sleep stages.

Chronic sleep deprivation has serious consequences. Beyond obvious effects like impaired attention and reaction time, insufficient sleep increases risks for obesity, diabetes, cardiovascular disease, and depression. The immune system weakens, making sleep-deprived individuals more susceptible to infections. Despite this knowledge, many people chronically undersleep, sacrificing health for productivity that actually decreases without adequate rest.`,
