        id: 'gre_55', category: 'GRE', topic: '文化研究', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Globalization and Cultural Identity',
        passage: `Globalization has intensified cultural exchange on an unprecedented scale, sparking debates about its effects on cultural diversity and identity. Critics warn of cultural homogenization, as Western—particularly American—products, values, and lifestyles spread worldwide. Supporters emphasize how globalization creates new hybrid cultures and expands choices for individuals everywhere.

The homogenization thesis points to the global spread of McDonald's, Hollywood films, and English language as evidence of cultural flattening. Local traditions, languages, and ways of life face pressure from commercially powerful global culture. Small languages die as younger generations shift to dominant tongues. Indigenous knowledge systems erode as formal education promotes standardized curricula.

However, the homogenization narrative oversimplifies complex processes. Cultural flows are not unidirectional; Korean pop music conquers global markets, yoga studios proliferate in Western cities, and cuisine everywhere grows more diverse. Anthropologists document how communities creolize imported elements, blending them with local traditions to create new cultural forms. McDonald's menus vary significantly across countries, adapted to local tastes.

Perhaps most importantly, globalization has fueled cultural revitalization movements. Facing perceived threats, many communities have renewed efforts to preserve and promote traditional languages, practices, and identities. The internet enables diaspora communities to maintain cultural connections across distances. Globalization thus produces both homogenizing and diversifying pressures, with outcomes depending on local contexts and choices.`,
