        id: 'gre_58', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '生态学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Invasive Species and Ecosystem Disruption',
        passage: `Invasive species—organisms introduced to environments where they did not evolve—rank among the leading causes of biodiversity loss worldwide. Freed from natural predators, diseases, and competitors that kept their populations in check, invasive species can multiply rapidly and devastate native ecosystems.

The mechanisms of harm vary. Some invasive species directly prey on native organisms lacking evolved defenses. The brown tree snake, accidentally introduced to Guam after World War II, drove most native forest birds to extinction. Other invasives outcompete natives for resources. Zebra mussels, transported to North America in ship ballast water, filter enormous quantities of plankton, starving native species and disrupting food webs.

Invasive plants can transform entire ecosystems. In the American Southeast, kudzu vines smother native vegetation, growing up to a foot per day during summer. In Australia, introduced rabbits so thoroughly consumed native plants that they triggered erosion and eliminated habitat for native animals. Removing established invasives proves extremely difficult and expensive.

Prevention remains the most effective strategy. Biosecurity measures screen cargo and travelers to prevent accidental introductions. Regulations restrict intentional import of potentially invasive species. Early detection and rapid response programs can eradicate new invasions before populations establish. Climate change complicates these efforts by enabling species to survive in previously unsuitable regions and creating new invasion pathways.`,
