        id: 'gre_59', category: 'GRE', topic: '心理学史', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'The Unconscious Mind: From Freud to Neuroscience',
        passage: `Sigmund Freud's concept of the unconscious mind revolutionized psychology in the early 20th century. Freud proposed that much of mental life operates below conscious awareness, driven by repressed desires and childhood experiences that shape behavior in ways we don't recognize. While many specific Freudian theories have been discredited, the broader notion of unconscious processing has been vindicated by cognitive neuroscience.

Freud's unconscious was dynamic and motivated—a seething cauldron of repressed sexual and aggressive impulses struggling against conscious defenses. Dreams, slips of the tongue, and neurotic symptoms revealed this hidden mental life. Psychoanalytic therapy aimed to bring unconscious material into consciousness, where it could be rationally addressed.

Modern cognitive science reconceptualized the unconscious as the "cognitive unconscious"—automatic mental processes that operate efficiently outside awareness. We unconsciously perceive, remember, and make judgments without deliberate thought. Priming studies show that stimuli presented too briefly for conscious perception nonetheless influence subsequent behavior. Implicit memories shape responses even when we cannot explicitly recall learning.

Neuroscience has confirmed that most brain activity occurs without conscious awareness. The brain processes enormous amounts of information, with consciousness accessing only a tiny fraction. Decisions sometimes appear in brain activity before people consciously experience choosing. This evidence supports a humbler view of conscious control than either folk psychology or traditional philosophy assumed—though it remains unclear exactly how much Freud got right about the specific contents and dynamics of unconscious mental life.`,
