        id: 'gre_61', category: 'GRE', topic: '神经科学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Mirror Neurons and Social Cognition',
        passage: `The discovery of mirror neurons in the early 1990s generated excitement about understanding the neural basis of social cognition. These neurons, first identified in macaque monkeys, fire both when an animal performs an action and when it observes another performing the same action. Some researchers claimed mirror neurons could explain imitation, empathy, language evolution, and even autism.

The initial discovery came from researchers studying motor control in monkeys. They noticed that certain neurons in the premotor cortex activated not only when a monkey grasped food but also when it watched a researcher grasp food. This "mirroring" suggested a direct neural link between observation and action, potentially enabling understanding of others' actions through internal simulation.

Enthusiasm led to bold claims. Vilayanur Ramachandran called mirror neurons "the driving force behind the great leap forward in human evolution." Some proposed that autism resulted from "broken mirrors"—dysfunctional mirror neuron systems preventing understanding of others' minds and actions. Mirror neurons became perhaps the most hyped concept in neuroscience.

However, subsequent research has tempered these claims. Studies in humans have produced mixed results about whether true mirror neurons exist or instead reflect learned associations. The mirror neuron theory of autism has not been consistently supported. Critics argue that mirror neurons, even if they exist as described, cannot alone explain complex social cognition. The concept remains influential but contested, illustrating how preliminary findings can be prematurely generalized.`,
