        id: 'gre_62', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '环境工程', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Wastewater Treatment and Water Recycling',
        passage: `As freshwater resources face increasing pressure from population growth and climate change, wastewater treatment and recycling have become critical components of sustainable water management. Modern treatment processes can transform sewage into water clean enough for irrigation, industrial use, and even drinking—though this last application faces psychological barriers.

Conventional wastewater treatment occurs in stages. Primary treatment uses physical processes—screens and settling tanks—to remove large solids. Secondary treatment employs microorganisms to break down organic matter; bacteria consume pollutants, then settle out as sludge. Tertiary treatment removes remaining nutrients and pathogens through filtration, chemical treatment, or UV disinfection.

Advanced treatment for water reuse goes further. Reverse osmosis forces water through membranes with pores so small that even dissolved salts and viruses cannot pass. Advanced oxidation processes break down trace pharmaceuticals and other emerging contaminants. Multiple barriers ensure safety even if one treatment step fails.

Singapore and Orange County, California demonstrate successful water recycling at scale. Singapore's NEWater meets up to 40% of the nation's water demand, primarily for industrial use. Orange County's Groundwater Replenishment System injects treated wastewater into aquifers, where it eventually becomes drinking water. Public education campaigns have helped overcome the "yuck factor" that initially limited acceptance of recycled water.`,
