        id: 'gre_63', category: 'GRE', topic: '数学哲学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'The Foundations of Mathematics',
        passage: `The late 19th and early 20th centuries witnessed a crisis in the foundations of mathematics. Discoveries of paradoxes and inconsistencies in naive set theory threatened the logical basis of mathematical reasoning. Three major schools emerged with competing visions of how to secure mathematics' foundations: logicism, formalism, and intuitionism.

Logicism, championed by Frege, Russell, and Whitehead, sought to reduce mathematics to pure logic. If mathematical truths could be derived from logical axioms using logical rules, mathematics would inherit logic's certainty. Russell and Whitehead's massive "Principia Mathematica" attempted this reduction, but the project encountered difficulties. Russell's own paradox—concerning the set of all sets that don't contain themselves—showed that naive set theory was inconsistent.

Formalism, associated with David Hilbert, took a different approach. Hilbert proposed treating mathematics as a formal game with symbols manipulated according to explicit rules. The goal was proving that mathematical systems were consistent (free from contradiction) and complete (capable of proving all true statements). Gödel's incompleteness theorems devastated this program, showing that any sufficiently powerful consistent system cannot prove its own consistency and must contain true statements it cannot prove.

Intuitionism, developed by Brouwer, rejected the completed infinite and non-constructive proofs. For intuitionists, mathematical objects exist only if they can be mentally constructed. This requires revising classical logic, rejecting the law of excluded middle (that every statement is either true or false) for infinite domains. While few mathematicians adopted intuitionism fully, constructive mathematics remains an active research area with connections to computer science.`,
