        id: 'gre_66', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '考古学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Dating the Past: Archaeological Methods',
        passage: `Archaeologists use various methods to determine the age of artifacts and sites. These dating techniques fall into two categories: relative dating, which establishes sequences without specific dates, and absolute dating, which provides actual ages. Together, these methods allow reconstruction of human prehistory with increasing precision.

Stratigraphy, the study of rock and soil layers, provides the foundation for relative dating. Objects found in deeper layers are generally older than those above, following the principle of superposition. Seriation arranges artifacts by stylistic changes over time; pottery styles, for example, evolve in recognizable patterns. These methods establish chronological sequences even without knowing precise dates.

Radiocarbon dating, developed by Willard Libby in 1949, revolutionized archaeology by providing absolute dates. Living organisms absorb carbon-14, a radioactive isotope, from the atmosphere. After death, carbon-14 decays at a known rate (half-life of about 5,730 years). Measuring remaining carbon-14 in organic materials—wood, bone, charcoal—reveals how long ago the organism died. The method is effective for materials up to about 50,000 years old.

Other absolute methods extend archaeology's reach. Potassium-argon dating, measuring decay in volcanic rocks, dates human ancestors millions of years old. Thermoluminescence dates when clay was last heated, useful for pottery and fire-hardened stones. Dendrochronology, or tree-ring dating, provides year-by-year precision where suitable wood survives. Each method has limitations, and archaeologists typically use multiple techniques to cross-check results.`,
