        id: 'gre_68', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '物理学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'The Science of Sound',
        passage: `Sound is a mechanical wave that travels through matter—air, water, or solids—by vibrating particles. Unlike electromagnetic waves such as light, sound requires a medium and cannot travel through vacuum. Understanding sound physics has applications from music and architecture to medical imaging and animal communication.

Sound waves are characterized by frequency, wavelength, and amplitude. Frequency, measured in hertz (Hz), determines pitch—higher frequencies produce higher-pitched sounds. Human hearing ranges from about 20 Hz to 20,000 Hz, though this range narrows with age. Amplitude, the wave's height, determines loudness, measured in decibels. The relationship is logarithmic: each 10-decibel increase represents roughly doubling of perceived loudness.

Sound travels at different speeds through different media. In air at room temperature, sound moves at approximately 343 meters per second—much slower than light, explaining why we see lightning before hearing thunder. Sound travels faster in water (about 1,500 m/s) and even faster in solids like steel (about 5,000 m/s). Temperature also affects speed; sound travels faster in warmer air as molecules move more energetically.

The Doppler effect describes how motion affects perceived frequency. When a sound source approaches, waves compress and frequency increases; when it recedes, waves stretch and frequency decreases. This explains why a siren sounds higher as an ambulance approaches and lower as it passes. The Doppler effect has numerous applications, from weather radar to measuring blood flow in medical ultrasound.`,
