        title: 'The Cardiovascular System',
        passage: `The cardiovascular system, consisting of the heart, blood vessels, and blood, delivers oxygen and nutrients throughout the body while removing metabolic waste. This remarkable system pumps approximately 7,500 liters of blood daily through roughly 100,000 kilometers of vessels—enough to circle Earth twice.

The heart, a muscular organ about the size of a fist, functions as a dual pump. The right side receives deoxygenated blood from the body and pumps it to the lungs for oxygen. The left side receives oxygenated blood from the lungs and pumps it to the body. Four chambers—two atria receiving blood and two ventricles pumping it out—coordinate through electrical signals that produce the heartbeat.

Blood vessels form a closed circuit. Arteries carry blood away from the heart, branching into smaller arterioles and finally capillaries—microscopic vessels where gas and nutrient exchange occurs. Blood then returns through venules and veins to the heart. Arterial walls are thick and elastic to handle high pressure; veins have thinner walls and contain valves preventing backflow.

Cardiovascular disease remains the leading cause of death globally. Atherosclerosis—buildup of fatty plaques in arteries—restricts blood flow and can cause heart attacks and strokes. Risk factors include high blood pressure, high cholesterol, smoking, obesity, diabetes, and sedentary lifestyle. Most cardiovascular disease is preventable through lifestyle modifications: regular exercise, healthy diet, not smoking, and maintaining healthy weight.`,
