        id: 'gre_71', category: 'GRE', topic: '语言学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Language Acquisition: Nature vs. Nurture',
        passage: `How children acquire language remains one of cognitive science's most fascinating puzzles. By age five, most children have mastered the complex grammatical rules of their native language without formal instruction—an achievement that has fueled decades of debate between nativist and empiricist approaches.

Noam Chomsky's nativist theory proposes that humans possess an innate "language acquisition device" containing universal grammar—abstract principles common to all languages. Children don't learn language from scratch but rather set parameters within this pre-existing framework based on input they hear. This explains why children acquire language rapidly, make systematic errors (saying "goed" instead of "went"), and master complex structures their input cannot fully explain.

Empiricist approaches counter that statistical learning and social interaction suffice to explain language acquisition. Infants are remarkably sensitive to statistical patterns in speech—they can segment words from continuous speech streams after brief exposure. Connectionist models demonstrate that neural networks can learn grammatical patterns without built-in rules. Social cues from caregivers guide attention and provide feedback.

Contemporary researchers increasingly seek integration rather than choosing sides. Innate constraints likely interact with learning mechanisms and social input. The poverty of the stimulus argument—that input is too impoverished to explain acquisition—has been challenged by research showing richer input than previously assumed. Yet the speed and uniformity of acquisition across diverse environments suggests that children bring something special to the task.`,
