        title: 'Glaciers and Climate Change',
        passage: `Glaciers, massive rivers of ice formed from accumulated snowfall over centuries, serve as sensitive indicators of climate change. As global temperatures rise, glaciers worldwide are retreating at accelerating rates, with profound implications for water supplies, sea levels, and ecosystems.

Glaciers form when winter snowfall exceeds summer melting over many years. The accumulated snow compresses into dense ice that slowly flows downhill under its own weight. At lower elevations, the glacier melts, releasing water that feeds rivers and streams. This balance between accumulation and melting determines whether a glacier grows or shrinks.

Since the mid-19th century, the majority of Earth's glaciers have been retreating. Alpine glaciers in Europe, North America, and the Andes have lost substantial ice mass. Himalayan glaciers, which supply water to over a billion people, are thinning at alarming rates. Arctic and Antarctic ice sheets, containing enough ice to raise sea levels by dozens of meters, show signs of accelerating loss.

The consequences are far-reaching. Many communities depend on glacial meltwater for drinking water, irrigation, and hydroelectric power. As glaciers shrink, seasonal water availability changes—initially increasing as stored ice melts, then decreasing as glaciers disappear entirely. Coastal communities face rising seas as ice enters the ocean. Mountain ecosystems adapted to cold conditions migrate upward until they have nowhere left to go.`,
