        title: 'The New Deal and American Liberalism',
        passage: `Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal programs of the 1930s fundamentally reshaped the relationship between the American government and its citizens. In response to the Great Depression's devastation, the New Deal vastly expanded federal intervention in the economy and established a social safety net that persists today. Yet historians continue to debate its effectiveness and long-term implications.

The New Deal proceeded in phases. The first "hundred days" addressed immediate emergencies: bank stabilization, agricultural relief, unemployment programs. The second New Deal (1935-1936) created lasting institutions including Social Security, the National Labor Relations Act protecting union rights, and the Works Progress Administration employing millions. These programs represented an unprecedented federal commitment to economic security.

Critics attacked from both left and right. Conservatives denounced the New Deal as socialism, warning that government intervention would destroy individual initiative and free markets. Radicals like Huey Long argued it didn't go far enough, failing to redistribute wealth adequately. Business leaders resented regulation and taxation, though many accepted reforms as alternatives to more radical change.

Historians assess the New Deal's legacy differently. It clearly did not end the Depression—full recovery came only with World War II spending. Yet it may have prevented worse outcomes, stabilizing a collapsing system and providing hope. More fundamentally, it established expectations that government should cushion economic hardship, creating a template for modern liberalism. The debates it sparked about government's proper role continue to define American politics.`,
