        id: 'gre_74', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '生物化学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Enzymes: Biological Catalysts',
        passage: `Enzymes are protein molecules that act as biological catalysts, dramatically accelerating chemical reactions in living organisms. Without enzymes, most biochemical reactions would occur too slowly to sustain life. A single enzyme molecule can catalyze thousands of reactions per second, making them extraordinarily efficient.

Enzymes work by lowering the activation energy required for reactions to proceed. Each enzyme has an "active site" where substrate molecules bind and undergo transformation. The lock-and-key model suggests substrates fit precisely into active sites; the induced-fit model proposes that both enzyme and substrate change shape upon binding. Either way, this specificity ensures enzymes catalyze only particular reactions.

Several factors affect enzyme activity. Temperature generally increases reaction rates until enzymes denature—lose their three-dimensional shape—at high temperatures. Each enzyme has an optimal pH; deviation causes structural changes that reduce activity. Substrate concentration affects reaction rates until all enzyme molecules are occupied. Inhibitors—molecules that reduce enzyme activity—can be competitive (blocking the active site) or non-competitive (changing enzyme shape).

Enzymes have countless applications beyond their natural roles. Food processing uses enzymes to tenderize meat, clarify fruit juice, and produce cheese. Laundry detergents contain enzymes that break down protein and fat stains. Medical diagnostics measure enzyme levels in blood to detect tissue damage. Biotechnology engineers enzymes for industrial processes and therapeutic applications.`,
