        title: 'The Ozone Layer: Earth\'s Sunscreen',
        passage: `The ozone layer, located in the stratosphere 15 to 35 kilometers above Earth's surface, absorbs most of the sun's harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation. Without this protective shield, life on land would be impossible—UV radiation damages DNA, causes skin cancer, and harms ecosystems. The discovery that human activities were destroying the ozone layer led to one of environmental policy's greatest successes.

Ozone (O3) forms when UV radiation splits oxygen molecules (O2), and the freed atoms combine with other O2 molecules. This process absorbs UV energy, preventing it from reaching the surface. Ozone is constantly created and destroyed in a natural cycle, maintaining a stable protective layer under normal conditions.

In the 1970s, scientists discovered that chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs)—chemicals used in refrigerators, air conditioners, and aerosol sprays—were destroying ozone. CFCs drift into the stratosphere, where UV radiation breaks them apart, releasing chlorine atoms. Each chlorine atom can destroy thousands of ozone molecules before being removed. By the 1980s, a severe ozone "hole" appeared over Antarctica each spring.

The 1987 Montreal Protocol banned CFC production, becoming perhaps the most successful international environmental agreement. Ozone-depleting substances have declined dramatically. Scientists project that the ozone layer will return to 1980 levels by mid-century. This success demonstrates that coordinated international action can address global environmental threats—a lesson relevant to climate change, which presents even greater challenges.`,
