        title: 'Ocean Currents and Climate',
        passage: `Ocean currents—large-scale movements of seawater—play crucial roles in regulating global climate by distributing heat around the planet. Surface currents, driven primarily by winds, and deep currents, driven by differences in water density, together form a global "conveyor belt" that influences weather patterns, marine ecosystems, and coastal climates.

Surface currents respond to prevailing winds but are deflected by the Coriolis effect—an apparent force resulting from Earth's rotation. In the Northern Hemisphere, currents curve to the right; in the Southern Hemisphere, to the left. These patterns create large circular flows called gyres. The Gulf Stream, part of the North Atlantic gyre, carries warm water from the tropics northward, warming Western Europe's climate.

Thermohaline circulation drives deep ocean currents. In polar regions, surface water becomes cold and salty (as ice forms, salt is expelled), making it denser. This dense water sinks and flows along the ocean floor toward the equator. Eventually, it rises in warmer regions, completing a cycle that takes roughly 1,000 years. This circulation moves enormous amounts of heat and carbon dioxide through the ocean.

Climate change threatens ocean circulation patterns. Melting ice sheets add fresh water to polar oceans, potentially reducing the density differences that drive thermohaline circulation. Some models predict weakening of the Gulf Stream, which could paradoxically cool Northwestern Europe even as global temperatures rise. Changes in ocean currents could also affect marine fisheries and precipitation patterns worldwide.`,
