        title: 'Photography and the Question of Art',
        passage: `When photography emerged in the 1830s, it provoked intense debate about its status as art. Could a mechanical process, seemingly requiring no human skill, produce art? The debate illuminates fundamental questions about creativity, authorship, and the nature of artistic expression that remain relevant in our digital age of AI-generated images.

Early critics dismissed photography as mere mechanical reproduction. Baudelaire called it "art's most mortal enemy," fearing it would corrupt taste by prioritizing realistic documentation over imaginative creation. Painters felt threatened, particularly in portraiture where photography quickly dominated. If a machine could capture likeness, what was the painter's purpose?

Defenders argued that photography required aesthetic judgment—composition, lighting, timing, and subject selection all reflected the photographer's vision. The photograph was not simply a transparent record but an interpretation shaped by human choices. Alfred Stieglitz and the Photo-Secession movement consciously demonstrated photography's artistic potential through carefully crafted images rivaling painting in beauty and expressiveness.

The debate evolved rather than resolved. Photography gained acceptance as art while continuing to serve documentary and commercial functions. Distinctions between "art photography" and everyday snapshots emerged. Contemporary digital manipulation further blurs boundaries—when does editing transform documentation into creation? The recurring question of whether new technologies can produce art echoes through debates about computer-generated imagery, auto-tuned music, and now AI creativity.`,
