        title: 'Epigenetics: Beyond the Genetic Code',
        passage: `For decades, scientists believed that DNA sequence alone determined biological traits. Epigenetics has revolutionized this view by revealing how gene expression can be modified without changing the underlying DNA sequence. These modifications can persist through cell divisions and sometimes across generations, adding a new layer of complexity to inheritance.

Epigenetic mechanisms include DNA methylation and histone modification. In methylation, small chemical groups attach to DNA, typically silencing gene expression. Histones are proteins around which DNA wraps; chemical modifications to histones can make genes more or less accessible for expression. These "marks" act like switches, turning genes on or off in response to developmental signals and environmental cues.

Environmental factors can trigger epigenetic changes. Nutrition, stress, toxin exposure, and even social experiences can modify gene expression patterns. Studies of Dutch famine survivors showed that prenatal malnutrition affected not only those exposed but their children and grandchildren. Honeybees demonstrate dramatic epigenetic effects: genetically identical larvae become queens or workers depending on what they're fed.

Epigenetics has medical implications. Cancer cells often show abnormal methylation patterns. Some epigenetic modifications may be reversible with drugs, offering therapeutic possibilities. The field also raises questions about inheritance beyond classical genetics—can acquired characteristics be transmitted? While Lamarck's specific proposals were wrong, epigenetic inheritance suggests that experience can sometimes affect offspring in ways traditional genetics did not anticipate.`,
