        id: 'gre_82', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '进化生物学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Convergent Evolution: Similar Solutions to Similar Problems',
        passage: `Convergent evolution occurs when unrelated species independently evolve similar features in response to similar environmental pressures. These analogous structures arise not from shared ancestry but from facing comparable challenges. Convergent evolution provides powerful evidence for natural selection's ability to shape organisms toward adaptive solutions.

Eyes have evolved independently at least 40 times across the animal kingdom. Octopus and human eyes are remarkably similar—both have lenses, irises, and retinas—yet evolved completely separately. Both lineages faced the same challenge: detecting light and forming images in a marine or terrestrial environment. Natural selection found similar solutions despite different starting points.

Wings provide another striking example. Bats, birds, and insects all developed flight independently. While the structures differ in detail—bird wings have feathers, bat wings use skin membranes, insect wings are chitinous—all solve the aerodynamic problem of generating lift. Even among mammals, powered flight evolved only in bats, while gliding evolved independently in flying squirrels, sugar gliders, and colugos.

Convergent evolution can mislead taxonomists who classify organisms based on physical similarity. Dolphins and ichthyosaurs (extinct marine reptiles) look remarkably similar—streamlined bodies, dorsal fins, flippers—but are only distantly related. Both evolved from land-dwelling ancestors and independently developed adaptations for swimming in open oceans. Molecular techniques now allow scientists to distinguish true relatedness from convergent similarity.`,
