        id: 'gre_83', category: 'GRE', topic: '科学社会学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'The Social Construction of Scientific Knowledge',
        passage: `The sociology of scientific knowledge (SSK) examines how social factors influence the content of science itself—not just its funding or applications, but the knowledge claims scientists make. This approach, developed in the 1970s and 1980s, challenged the traditional view that scientific knowledge simply mirrors an objective natural world, arguing instead that science is shaped by social processes like any other human activity.

The strong programme in SSK, articulated by David Bloor, proposed that sociological explanations should apply equally to beliefs considered true and those considered false. Traditional accounts explained true beliefs by their correspondence to reality and false beliefs by social or psychological factors. Bloor argued this asymmetry was unjustified: the same types of causes—social, cultural, institutional—should explain all beliefs.

Laboratory studies by Bruno Latour, Karin Knorr-Cetina, and others observed scientists at work, documenting how experimental results are negotiated, contested, and ultimately stabilized as "facts." These studies revealed science as a messier, more socially contingent process than textbook accounts suggest. What counts as evidence, how instruments are calibrated, which anomalies are dismissed—all involve interpretive judgments shaped by training, culture, and interests.

Critics accuse SSK of relativism—implying that scientific knowledge is no more valid than any other belief system. Defenders respond that describing science as socially constructed doesn't deny its effectiveness; it simply recognizes that the path to knowledge involves human choices and negotiations. The debate continues, but SSK has permanently complicated naive realism about scientific objectivity.`,
