        title: 'Earthquakes: Causes and Prediction',
        passage: `Earthquakes result from sudden release of energy accumulated in Earth's crust, typically along fault lines where tectonic plates meet. When stress exceeds rock strength, rocks rupture and slide, releasing seismic waves that shake the ground. Understanding earthquakes has improved dramatically, yet accurate prediction remains elusive.

Most earthquakes occur at plate boundaries. At convergent boundaries, one plate subducts beneath another, generating the world's largest earthquakes. The 2011 Japan earthquake (magnitude 9.1) and 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake (magnitude 9.1-9.3) both occurred at subduction zones. Transform boundaries, where plates slide horizontally past each other, produce earthquakes like those along California's San Andreas Fault. Divergent boundaries and intraplate regions also experience seismicity, though typically less severe.

Scientists measure earthquake size using magnitude scales. The Richter scale, though still popularly referenced, has been superseded by the moment magnitude scale for large earthquakes. Each whole number increase represents roughly 32 times more energy release. A magnitude 8 earthquake releases about 1,000 times more energy than a magnitude 6.

Despite understanding earthquake mechanisms, prediction—specifying when, where, and how large—remains beyond current capabilities. Short-term precursors like foreshocks, ground deformation, and groundwater changes have proven unreliable. Instead, scientists focus on long-term hazard assessment and preparation: identifying high-risk zones, developing building codes, and creating early warning systems that detect initial waves and alert populations before stronger shaking arrives.`,
