        title: 'Soil: The Foundation of Agriculture',
        passage: `Soil, a complex mixture of minerals, organic matter, water, air, and living organisms, forms the foundation of terrestrial agriculture. Healthy soil supports plant growth, filters water, stores carbon, and hosts enormous biodiversity. Yet soil degradation threatens agricultural productivity worldwide, with serious implications for food security.

Soil forms over centuries through weathering of rock and accumulation of organic matter. Different soil types result from variations in parent rock, climate, topography, organisms, and time. Loam—a balanced mixture of sand, silt, and clay—is ideal for most crops, retaining water and nutrients while allowing drainage. Soil structure, the arrangement of particles into aggregates, affects root penetration and water movement.

Soil fertility depends on nutrients available to plants. Nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium are macronutrients required in large quantities. Micronutrients like iron, zinc, and manganese are needed in smaller amounts. Organic matter—decomposed plant and animal material—improves soil structure, retains water, and slowly releases nutrients. Soil organisms from bacteria to earthworms cycle nutrients and maintain soil health.

Agricultural practices can either build or destroy soil. Continuous cultivation, especially with heavy machinery, compacts soil and destroys structure. Monoculture depletes specific nutrients and encourages pests. Erosion removes topsoil containing most nutrients and organic matter. Sustainable practices—crop rotation, cover cropping, reduced tillage, composting—can maintain and improve soil health, supporting long-term productivity.`,
