        title: 'Federalism: Dividing Power',
        passage: `Federalism divides governmental authority between central and regional governments, each sovereign within its sphere. This arrangement, found in countries from the United States to Germany to India, offers potential benefits—accommodating diversity, enabling experimentation, preventing tyranny—while creating challenges of coordination, inconsistency, and potential conflict between levels.

The American Constitution established federalism to balance national unity with state autonomy. Enumerated powers belong to the federal government; reserved powers remain with states. This division has been contested throughout American history, from early debates between Hamilton and Jefferson through the Civil War to contemporary disputes over healthcare, immigration, and environmental policy.

Federal systems vary considerably in design. Some allocate different policy areas to different levels (legislative federalism); others give both levels concurrent authority over the same areas (administrative federalism). Some protect regional governments constitutionally; others allow central revision of regional powers. Fiscal federalism concerns how revenues are raised and distributed—whether regions collect their own taxes or depend on central transfers.

Federalism interacts complexly with democracy. Regional governments can serve as "laboratories of democracy," testing policies before national adoption. They may also better represent local preferences and enable participation in smaller polities. However, federalism can obstruct majority will, enable local oppression of minorities, and create accountability gaps where neither level takes responsibility. The optimal balance depends on specific circumstances and values—there is no one-size-fits-all federal design.`,
