        title: 'Plastics: Benefits and Environmental Challenges',
        passage: `Plastics, synthetic polymers derived primarily from petroleum, have transformed modern life. Their versatility, durability, and low cost have made them ubiquitous in packaging, construction, healthcare, and countless other applications. Yet the same properties that make plastics useful create serious environmental problems when they become waste.

Plastics are polymers—long chains of repeating molecular units. Different monomers and arrangements produce plastics with different properties: flexible polyethylene for bags, rigid PVC for pipes, transparent polycarbonate for bottles. Additives enhance specific properties like flexibility, color, or UV resistance. This chemical variety enables diverse applications but complicates recycling.

The environmental impact of plastic waste has reached crisis levels. Approximately 400 million tons of plastic are produced annually, with much becoming single-use packaging discarded within months. Plastics persist in the environment for centuries. Ocean plastic harms marine life through entanglement and ingestion. Microplastics—tiny fragments from degrading larger pieces—have been found in water, soil, air, food, and human tissues.

Solutions involve reducing production, improving recycling, and developing alternatives. Many jurisdictions ban single-use plastic items. Chemical recycling can break polymers back into monomers for reuse. Biodegradable plastics made from plant materials decompose more readily, though they require specific conditions. No single solution suffices; addressing plastic pollution requires systemic changes across production, consumption, and waste management.`,
