        id: 'gre_91', category: 'GRE', topic: '认知科学', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Consciousness: The Hard Problem',
        passage: `Consciousness—subjective, first-person experience—remains one of science's deepest mysteries. Philosopher David Chalmers distinguished the "easy problems" of consciousness (explaining cognitive functions like attention, memory, and language processing) from the "hard problem": why is there subjective experience at all? Why does brain activity feel like anything from the inside?

The easy problems, though technically challenging, seem solvable through neuroscience. We can explain how the brain processes visual information, stores memories, and produces behavior. But explaining why information processing is accompanied by conscious experience—the redness of red, the taste of coffee, the feeling of pain—requires something more. This explanatory gap between physical processes and subjective qualities has proven remarkably difficult to bridge.

Several philosophical positions address this puzzle. Physicalists argue that consciousness will eventually be explained by neuroscience, even if we don't yet know how. Property dualists accept physical explanations of brain function but argue that conscious properties are fundamental features of reality not reducible to physics. Panpsychists suggest consciousness is ubiquitous in nature, with human consciousness being a complex form of something present even in simple matter.

The hard problem has practical implications. Artificial intelligence raises questions about machine consciousness—can computers ever be truly conscious, or merely simulate intelligence? Medical ethics confronts questions about consciousness in coma patients or fetuses. Understanding consciousness matters for understanding ourselves and navigating these difficult questions.`,
