        id: 'gre_92', category: 'TOEFL', topic: '海洋学', difficulty: '中级',
        title: 'Coral Reefs: Biodiversity Hotspots in Crisis',
        passage: `Coral reefs, covering less than 1% of the ocean floor, support approximately 25% of all marine species. These underwater ecosystems, built by tiny coral polyps secreting calcium carbonate skeletons, provide habitat, breeding grounds, and food sources for countless organisms. Yet coral reefs worldwide are experiencing unprecedented decline.

Corals live in symbiosis with microscopic algae called zooxanthellae, which photosynthesize and provide most of the coral's energy. This relationship makes corals highly sensitive to environmental changes. When stressed by warming waters, corals expel their algae, turning white in a process called bleaching. If conditions don't improve quickly, bleached corals die. Global ocean temperatures have caused mass bleaching events with increasing frequency.

Beyond warming, reefs face multiple threats. Ocean acidification, caused by absorbed CO2, reduces the availability of carbonate ions corals need for skeleton building. Pollution from agricultural runoff causes algal blooms that smother corals. Overfishing disrupts reef ecosystems, and destructive fishing practices physically damage reef structures. Local stresses compound global climate impacts.

Conservation efforts operate at multiple scales. Marine protected areas limit fishing and development. Coral restoration projects transplant lab-raised corals to degraded reefs. Scientists research heat-resistant coral varieties for assisted evolution. However, without addressing climate change—the primary driver of reef decline—local conservation efforts may prove insufficient. The fate of coral reefs depends on global action to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.`,
