        id: 'gre_93', category: 'GRE', topic: '法律理论', difficulty: '高级',
        title: 'Natural Law vs. Legal Positivism',
        passage: `The nature of law has been debated since antiquity. Natural law theory holds that law derives its authority from moral principles inherent in nature or human reason. Legal positivism, by contrast, argues that law is simply what sovereign authorities enact—its validity depends not on moral content but on proper procedures and social facts. This fundamental disagreement shapes legal philosophy and practice.

Natural law theory, traceable to Aristotle and developed by Thomas Aquinas, maintains that positive (human-made) law should conform to higher moral law. An unjust law, on this view, is not truly law at all—or at least lacks the full authority of law. This tradition influenced the development of human rights discourse and provides grounds for civil disobedience against unjust regimes.

Legal positivism, associated with thinkers like John Austin, Jeremy Bentham, and H.L.A. Hart, separates legal validity from moral evaluation. A law is valid if enacted through proper procedures, regardless of its moral content. This doesn't mean positivists approve of unjust laws—they simply distinguish the question "Is this valid law?" from "Is this law just?" Hart refined positivism by emphasizing law as a system of rules including secondary rules about how to create, change, and apply primary rules.

The debate has practical implications. Should judges interpret law based purely on enacted rules, or may they invoke moral principles? Can international human rights standards override domestic law? How should legal systems respond to laws that, while properly enacted, violate fundamental rights? Different answers to these questions reflect underlying commitments to natural law or positivist frameworks.`,
