        title: 'The Human Microbiome',
        passage: `The human body hosts trillions of microorganisms—bacteria, viruses, fungi, and other microbes—collectively called the microbiome. These microbes, numbering roughly equal to human cells, are not merely passengers but active participants in human physiology. Research has revealed the microbiome's crucial roles in digestion, immunity, and even mental health.

The gut microbiome, the most studied community, contains over 1,000 bacterial species. These bacteria break down dietary fiber humans cannot digest, producing short-chain fatty acids that nourish intestinal cells. They synthesize vitamins B and K. They train the immune system to distinguish harmless substances from threats. Disruption of gut microbiome balance—from antibiotics, poor diet, or stress—has been linked to conditions from inflammatory bowel disease to obesity.

The gut-brain axis describes bidirectional communication between gut microbes and the brain. Gut bacteria produce neurotransmitters like serotonin and GABA. Studies in mice show that germ-free animals (raised without microbes) display altered anxiety and social behaviors correctable by microbial colonization. Human studies suggest connections between microbiome composition and conditions like depression and autism, though causation remains difficult to establish.

Microbiome research has spawned interest in therapeutic interventions. Probiotics—live beneficial bacteria—and prebiotics—foods that feed beneficial bacteria—aim to improve microbiome health. Fecal microbiota transplantation, transferring stool from healthy donors, has proven effective against certain infections. Personalized medicine may eventually tailor treatments based on individual microbiome profiles.`,
