        title: 'Nuclear Energy: Promise and Controversy',
        passage: `Nuclear energy produces approximately 10% of global electricity through controlled nuclear fission—splitting heavy atoms like uranium to release enormous energy. Unlike fossil fuels, nuclear plants emit no greenhouse gases during operation, making nuclear attractive for addressing climate change. Yet concerns about safety, waste, and proliferation make it deeply controversial.

Nuclear fission occurs when neutrons strike uranium-235 nuclei, causing them to split and release energy plus more neutrons, creating a chain reaction. In reactors, this reaction is controlled to produce sustained heat, which generates steam to drive turbines. A single kilogram of uranium contains as much energy as several tons of coal, giving nuclear extraordinary energy density.

The 1986 Chernobyl and 2011 Fukushima disasters highlighted nuclear's risks. Both involved catastrophic releases of radioactive material with long-lasting environmental and health consequences. Modern reactor designs incorporate passive safety features that don't require human intervention or electrical power to prevent meltdowns. However, public fear persists, and major accidents, though rare, have enormous consequences.

Nuclear waste presents another challenge. Spent fuel remains radioactive for thousands of years and requires secure long-term storage. No country has fully implemented permanent geological repositories. Additionally, nuclear technology's dual-use potential—civilian reactors producing plutonium usable in weapons—raises proliferation concerns. These challenges must be weighed against nuclear's role as a low-carbon energy source in climate mitigation strategies.`,
